    "abstract": "Channel state information at the transmitter (CSIT) is a key ingredient in realizing the multiplexing gain provided by distributed MIMO systems. For a downlink multiple-input single output (MISO) broadcast channel, with M antennas at the transmitters and K single antenna receivers, the maximum multiplexing gain or the maximum degrees of freedom (DoF) is min(M,K). The optimal DoF of min(M,K) is achievable if the transmitter has access to perfect, instantaneous CSIT from all receivers. In this paper, we pose the question that what is minimum amount of CSIT required per user in order to achieve the maximum DoF of min(M,K). By minimum amount of CSIT per user, we refer to the minimum fraction of time that the transmitter has access to perfect and instantaneous CSIT from a user. Through a novel converse proof and an achievable scheme, it is shown that the minimum fraction of time, perfect CSIT is required per user in order to achieve the DoF of min(M,K) is given by min(M,K)/K.",
